1. Read Data & Create Time Series

# Read data from csv into R
co2.data <- read.csv("annual-co2-emissions-per-country.csv") 
# all data from 1750 to 2019

#filter data
co2.world.data <- co2.data[co2.data$Entity == "World",]
co2.us.data <- co2.data[co2.data$Entity == "United States",]
co2.china.data <- co2.data[co2.data$Entity == "China",]
# create time series -- World
co2.world.ts <- ts(co2.world.data$Annual.CO2.emissions, start = c(1750), end = c(2019), frequency = 1)

# create time series -- United States
co2.us.ts <- ts(co2.us.data$Annual.CO2.emissions, start = c(1750), end = c(2019), frequency = 1)

# create time series -- China
co2.china.ts <- ts(co2.china.data$Annual.CO2.emissions, start = c(1750), end = c(2019), frequency = 1)

================================================================================= ### 2. World Data

# split data - approximately 70% training data, 30% validation data
co2.world.train <- window(co2.world.ts, end = c(1999))
co2.world.valid <- window(co2.world.ts, start = c(2000))
#check the length of each
length(co2.world.train)
## [1] 250
length(co2.world.valid)
## [1] 20
nValid = 20
World CO2 Emission Plot
autoplot(co2.world.ts, xlab = "Year", ylab = "World CO2 Emission")

Simple Models Plots: Naive, Mean, Random Walk with drift
autoplot(co2.world.train, xlab = "Year", ylab = "CO2 Emission") +
    autolayer(meanf(co2.world.train, h = 21), 
              series = "Mean", PI = FALSE) +
    autolayer(naive(co2.world.train, h = 21),
              series = "Naive", PI = FALSE) +
    autolayer(rwf(co2.world.train, drift = TRUE, h = 21),
              series = "Drift", PI = FALSE) +
    guides(colour = guide_legend(title = "Forecast"))

There is a clear increasing trend in the data across time. The relationship looks more like exponential, but we could try different models and compare.

I. Regression

(1) Linear Model
# fit linear model
world.lm <- tslm(co2.world.train ~ trend)
summary(world.lm)
## 
## Call:
## tslm(formula = co2.world.train ~ trend)

lines(world.lm.pred$fitted, lwd = 2, col = "blue")
lines(co2.world.ts)

# summary of performance
result_lm <- accuracy(world.lm.pred$mean, co2.world.valid)

II. Exponential Smoothing Model

#automated smoothing model
world.ses <- ets(co2.world.train, model = "ZZZ", restrict = FALSE, allow.multiplicative.trend = TRUE)
world.ses
## ETS(M,M,N) 
## 
## Call:
##  ets(y = co2.world.train, model = "ZZZ", restrict = FALSE, allow.multiplicative.trend = TRUE) 
## 
##   Smoothing parameters:
##     alpha = 0.7363 
##     beta  = 0.0357 
## 
##   Initial states:
##     l = 9089183.5974 
##     b = 1.0179 
## 
##   sigma:  0.0527
## 
##      AIC     AICc      BIC 
## 9926.967 9927.212 9944.574
world.ses.pred <- forecast(world.ses , h = nValid, level = 0)
plot(world.ses.pred, ylab = "CO2 Emission", xlab = "Year", 
     bty = "l", main = "World CO2 Emission w/ Smoothing Model", flty = 2, xlim =c(1949, 2019))

lines(world.ses.pred$fitted, lwd = 2, col ="blue")
lines(co2.world.ts)

result_ses <- accuracy(world.ses.pred$mean, co2.world.valid)
